dotphiles
=========

A framework of dotfiles for the usual terminal apps and shells.

Installation
============

### Quickstart

    git clone --recursive git@github.com:dotfiles/dotfiles.git ~/.dotfiles
    ./.dotfiles/dotsync/bin/dotsync -L

### Fork

Sign up for an account on [github][5] and fork the project

    git clone --recursive git@github.com:username/dotfiles.git ~/.dotfiles
    ./.dotfiles/dotsync/bin/dotsync -L

Configuration
=============

### [Dotsync][1]

Add your dotfiles and machine names to *dotsyncrc*

### [Zsh][2]

Add your own settings to *zshrc*, *zshenv*, *zlogin*, *zlogout* and *zprofile*

### [Bash][3]

Add your own settings to *bashrc*

### Git

Add your name, email and gpg keyid to *gitconfig*

Contribute
----------

This project would not exist without all of its users and [contributors][6].

If you have ideas on how to make the configuration easier to maintain or
improve its performance, do not hesitate to fork and send pull requests.

### Issue Reporting

   - Check that the [issue][7] has not already been reported.
   - Check that the [issue][7] has not already been fixed in the latest code.
   - Open an [issue][7] with a clear title and description in grammatically correct,
     complete sentences.

### Pull Request

   - Read [how to properly contribute to open source projects on GitHub][8].
   - Use a topic branch to easily amend a pull request later, if necessary.
   - Write [good commit messages][9].
   - Squash commits on the topic branch before opening a pull request.
   - Use the same coding style and spacing.
   - Open a [pull request][10] that relates to but one subject with a clear
     title and description in gramatically correct, complete sentences.

